text: A vector database stores data as numerical embeddings instead of traditional rows and columns. These embeddings capture the semantic meaning of text, images, or other data types.
Embeddings are dense numerical vectors generated by machine learning models. They represent semantic relationships, allowing systems to compare data by meaning rather than exact keywords.
Vector databases enable semantic search by finding the nearest vectors to a query embedding. This allows users to retrieve relevant information even when the wording is different.
ChromaDB is an open-source vector database designed for storing and querying embeddings efficiently. It supports similarity search and metadata filtering.
Semantic search improves search quality by understanding user intent instead of relying on keyword matching. This makes results more accurate and context-aware.
FastAPI is a modern Python framework used to build high-performance APIs. It supports asynchronous request handling and automatic API documentation.
In vector-based systems, text data is often split into smaller chunks before generating embeddings. Chunking improves retrieval accuracy and reduces memory usage.
Vector indexing techniques such as approximate nearest neighbor search improve performance when working with large datasets.
Scalability in vector databases is achieved through efficient indexing, sharding, and optimized storage of embeddings.
Ollama provides local large language models that can generate embeddings without relying on external APIs, improving privacy and control.
Embedding models transform raw text into numerical vectors that can be stored, searched, and compared efficiently.
Vector similarity search is commonly used in recommendation systems, question answering systems, and document retrieval applications.
Filtering and ranking strategies help remove irrelevant results from semantic search queries.
Vector databases are widely used in AI applications such as chatbots, knowledge bases, and enterprise search systems.
